    faq: [
      {
        q: 'What is the median home price in Downtown San Diego?',
        a: 'The median home price in Downtown San Diego is approximately $700,000 as of 2026. Entry-level studios and 1-bedroom condos in the Core District or East Village can start at $350,000–$500,000. Luxury high-rise units in the Marina District or Little Italy range from $1M to $4M+. Contact Hedda Parashos for current market conditions in specific neighborhoods.',
      },
      {
        q: 'Which neighborhoods are within Downtown San Diego?',
        a: 'Downtown San Diego comprises several distinct sub-markets: East Village (breweries, Petco Park, hip urban character), Little Italy (European dining scene, piazza, walkable), Gaslamp Quarter (historic entertainment district), Marina District (bayfront luxury high-rises), Cortez Hill (quieter, hillside views, more affordable), Columbia District (new office towers, growing residential), Core/Central Business District (value condos, transit access), and Bankers Hill (on the northern edge near Balboa Park — heritage homes and boutique buildings).',
      },
      {
        q: 'Is Downtown San Diego a good place for families?',
        a: 'Downtown can work for families who prioritize walkability and urban amenities over yard space and suburban schools. The proximity to Balboa Park, the waterfront, the Zoo, and museums is a genuine quality-of-life advantage. School quality varies significantly by building location — some addresses fall in the San Diego High feeder zone, others in Roosevelt International Middle (an excellent school). Verify your address\'s specific school assignments before purchasing.',
      },
      {
        q: 'What ZIP codes cover Downtown San Diego?',
        a: 'The primary ZIP code for Downtown San Diego is 92101, covering the Gaslamp Quarter, Marina District, East Village, Little Italy, and Cortez Hill. Bankers Hill and parts of the Core District also fall under 92103. When searching, using both ZIPs ensures you capture the full inventory of downtown-adjacent properties.',
      },
      {
        q: 'How walkable is Downtown San Diego?',
        a: 'Downtown San Diego has a Walk Score of 97 — one of the highest in the entire San Diego metropolitan area. Groceries, restaurants, gyms, parks, and entertainment are all walkable. The San Diego Trolley and the MTS bus network serve downtown from multiple stops, connecting residents to the airport, Mission Valley, SDSU, and the South Bay without a car. For daily errands and commuting within the county\'s urban core, downtown is unmatched.',
      },
      {
        q: 'What are HOA fees like in Downtown San Diego?',
        a: 'HOA fees in downtown vary widely. Older converted lofts and smaller buildings run $300–$550/month. Standard mid-rise condos (2BR) typically fall in the $450–$750 range. New luxury high-rises with concierge, rooftop decks, and fitness centers can reach $1,500–$2,000/month. Always review the HOA\'s reserve fund health and any pending special assessments — older buildings downtown sometimes carry deferred maintenance costs. Hedda can help you interpret HOA documents before making an offer.',
      },
      {
        q: 'What are the best areas in Downtown for first-time buyers?',
        a: 'First-time buyers in Downtown San Diego typically find the best value in the Core District (92101 Central), East Village, and Cortez Hill. These sub-neighborhoods have the highest inventory, the most competitive price-per-square-foot, and strong transit access. Cortez Hill offers elevated views and a quieter street life compared to the Gaslamp and East Village. As always in downtown, building age, HOA health, and parking availability are the key due-diligence items — contact Hedda for a building-by-building analysis.',
      },
    ],
    lifestyleBody: [
      'Life in Downtown San Diego rewards those who thrive on energy, access, and variety. Mornings unfold with a waterfront run along the Embarcadero, afternoons in Little Italy\'s outdoor piazza or browsing the Saturday farmers market, evenings at a Padres game at Petco Park or dinner at one of the neighborhood\'s Michelin-recognized restaurants. The bay is always visible from somewhere — a constant reminder that San Diego\'s world-class natural setting is built right into the city\'s DNA.',
      'The urban core has also matured as a tech and creative hub. Amazon, Illumina, and dozens of biotech and legal firms have downtown offices, putting residents and employers in the same walkable blocks. The trolley connects downtown to Mission Valley, SDSU, the South Bay, and the border without touching a freeway — a genuine urban advantage that only a handful of San Diego neighborhoods can claim.',
    ],
