    faq: [
      {
        q: 'What is the median home price in Mission Valley?',
        a: 'The median home price in Mission Valley is approximately $650,000 as of 2026. Entry-level condos in the Hotel Circle and Camino Del Rio areas can start as low as $400,000–$500,000, making Mission Valley one of the more accessible owner-occupant markets in central San Diego. Single-family homes in Mission Gorge and along the hillside pockets run $600,000–$1.3M. New construction along Riverwalk and Qualcomm Way commands a premium in the $700,000–$1.4M range. Contact Hedda Parashos for current market conditions.',
      },
      {
        q: 'What are the different neighborhoods within Mission Valley?',
        a: 'Mission Valley comprises several distinct sub-markets: Mission Valley West (Fashion Valley walkability, newer condos), Mission Valley East (value condos, Snapdragon Stadium proximity), Hotel Circle (older condo stock, golf adjacent, most affordable), Friars Road Corridor (river views, mid-century character), Mission Gorge (single-family homes, hillside setting, quieter), Camino Del Rio (commercial strip with dense condo development), Qualcomm Way (newer builds, tech employer proximity), and the Sports Arena / Midway District adjacent area (urban, investment-oriented).',
      },
      {
        q: 'Is Mission Valley a good place for families?',
        a: 'Mission Valley can work well for families, though it has a more urban character than traditional San Diego suburban neighborhoods. The Mission Gorge and Friars Road sub-markets offer more single-family homes, lower traffic density, and direct access to Mission Trails Regional Park. Families who value central location, easy school commutes, and quick access to SDSU, Snapdragon Stadium events, and Fashion Valley shopping will find Mission Valley genuinely appealing. Verify school district boundaries for your specific address.',
      },
      {
        q: 'What ZIP code covers Mission Valley?',
        a: 'The primary ZIP code for Mission Valley is 92108, which covers the valley floor from Hotel Circle in the west to Snapdragon Stadium in the east. Some adjacent areas along the valley\'s rim — including portions of Mission Gorge — also fall under 92120 (Del Cerro) or 92116 (Kensington/Normal Heights). Including all three ZIPs in your search ensures you capture the full range of Mission Valley-adjacent inventory.',
      },
      {
        q: 'What is the Riverwalk redevelopment and how does it affect property values?',
        a: 'The Riverwalk San Diego project is the redevelopment of the former Riverwalk Golf Club into a mixed-use urban village along the San Diego River. The full buildout envisions approximately 4,300 residential units, 152,000 square feet of retail, office space, parks, and a new Green Line trolley station — all within the western valley. Phase 1 construction is underway as of 2026. For buyers in Mission Valley West, this project represents significant long-term upside.',
      },
      {
        q: 'How far is Mission Valley from downtown San Diego?',
        a: 'Mission Valley is approximately 5–7 miles from downtown San Diego — a 10-minute drive via I-8 West in normal traffic. The San Diego Trolley\'s Green Line also connects Mission Valley to downtown with multiple stops along the valley corridor. SAN Airport is just 5 minutes away via the I-8/I-5 interchange, making Mission Valley one of the most airport-accessible neighborhoods in the entire county.',
      },
      {
        q: 'Are there single-family homes available in Mission Valley?',
        a: 'Yes, though Mission Valley is predominantly a condo and townhome market. Single-family homes are concentrated in Mission Gorge, along Friars Road\'s northern hillside, and in the quieter pockets north of I-8 near Camino Del Rio North. These SFR properties are generally well-maintained, benefit from larger lots, and carry lower HOA costs than comparable condo units. Inventory is limited and competition among buyers is strong.',
      },
      {
        q: 'What are HOA fees like in Mission Valley?',
        a: 'HOA fees in Mission Valley vary widely. Older condo complexes in Hotel Circle and Camino Del Rio typically run $200–$400/month. Standard condo developments across the valley floor range from $250–$500/month. Luxury or resort-style complexes with pools, fitness centers, and gated access can reach $850/month or more. New construction along the Riverwalk corridor falls in the $350–$650/month range. Single-family homes in Mission Gorge often have no HOA or a minimal ($0–$100) neighborhood association fee.',
      },
    ],
    lifestyleBody: [
      'Life in Mission Valley rewards those who prize convenience. Mornings start with a jog along the San Diego River Trail, afternoons unfold at Fashion Valley or over a round at Riverwalk Golf Club, and evenings find you at a stadium match or a rooftop table watching planes drift over the downtown skyline. The valley\'s flat geography and exceptional freeway access make it one of the easiest places in the county to actually live without a long commute dragging at your quality of life.',
      'The community is young, diverse, and rapidly evolving. SDSU\'s campus just minutes away brings intellectual energy, live music, and a revolving roster of restaurants and coffee shops. The trolley connects residents to Petco Park, the Gaslamp Quarter, and the Convention Center without touching a freeway — a genuine urban bonus most San Diego neighborhoods cannot offer.',
